04474nmm a2200649Ia 9781501727320DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017273207 a10.7591/97815017273202doi  a(DE-B1597)503545  a(OCoLC)1031947282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR535.F704a821/.3091 aKalas, Rayna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrame, Glass, Verse :bThe Technology of Poetic Invention in the English Renaissance /cRayna Kalas. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b22 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a book that draws attention to some of our most familiar and unquestioned habits of thought—from "framing" to "perspective" to "reflection"—Rayna Kalas suggests that metaphors of the poetic imagination were once distinctly material and technical in character. Kalas explores the visual culture of the English Renaissance by way of the poetic image, showing that English writers avoided charges of idolatry and fancy through conceits that were visual, but not pictorial. Frames, mirrors, and windows have been pervasive and enduring metaphors for texts from classical antiquity to modernity; as a result, those metaphors seem universally to emphasize the mimetic function of language, dividing reality from the text that represents it. This book dissociates those metaphors from their earlier and later formulations in order to demonstrate that figurative language was material in translating signs and images out of a sacred and iconic context and into an aesthetic and representational one. Reading specific poetic images—in works by Spenser, Shakespeare, Gascoigne, Bacon, and Nashe—together with material innovations in frames and glass, Kalas reveals both the immanence and the agency of figurative language in the early modern period.Frame, Glass, Verse shows, finally, how this earlier understanding of poetic language has been obscured by a modern idea of framing that has structured our apprehension of works of art, concepts, and even historical periods. Kalas presents archival research in the history of frames, mirrors, windows, lenses, and reliquaries that will be of interest to art historians, cultural theorists, historians of science, and literary critics alike. Throughout Frame, Glass, Verse, she challenges readers to rethink the relationship of poetry to technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aFrame-storiesxHistory and criticism. 0aInvention (Rhetoric). 0aMirrors in literature. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy16th century. 0aRenaissancezEngland. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism.  aFraming (or frames), materiality, technology, poetry, perspective, mirrors.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172732040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727320/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles